The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Ficci survey sees spurt in sales

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Nov. 27: India Inc is brimming with confidence and expects a demand-driven surge in sales, exports, employment and investment over the remaining months of the current financial year.

 According to a business confidence survey by the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry (Ficci) for the July-September period this year, 74 per cent of the respondent business firms perceive the current economic conditions moderately to substantially better than those in the previous six months. They also expect it to improve further over the next six months.

 The index for the economic conditions in the current round moved up nearly three points to 73.1 from 70.9 in the first-quarter survey. 

 Expectations index stood at 76.2, representing an increase of nearly two points from 74.8 recorded during the last round of survey.

 The overall business confidence index has also gone up from 73.5 to 75.2 ? a gain of 1.7 points ? in the current round. 

 At the micro level, too, companies are hopeful of a better business prospect in the coming six months. A majority of 83 per cent of the respondents revealed that they expected a higher to much higher sales in their respective businesses during the remaining months of the current fiscal. Another 29 per cent foresee an increase in prices, while a majority (65 per cent) of the business firms surveyed expect a higher to much higher profits.

 The upbeat mood is also reflected in the economys all-round performance. 




